[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]CBM[bold]&#xa0;[bold]CBM recognises that 
[normal]disability and
[normal] poverty are inextricably linked in a 
[normal]cycle 
[normal]-
[normal] disability
[normal] 
[normal]contributes to and deepens
[normal] poverty on an individual, family and community level
[normal],
[normal] and poverty 
[normal]is often a cause of disability
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]This means that poverty cannot be addressed without addressing disability.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CBM’s work is 
[normal]aligned to the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities and explicitly promotes inclusive development in relation to all articles, and with specific emphasis on articles 11 (humanitarian assistance) and article 33 (international cooperation
[normal]).
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CBM and Livelihoods[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]CBM’s strategic framework for livelihood development stresses the importance of inclusive approache
[normal]s to skills development, access to financial services, and paid employment, with the underlying aim of enabling persons with disabilities to become productive contributors to social insurance systems. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CBM is working actively with the Centre for Financial
[normal] Inclusion, an industry-facing think tank, at Accion (a global microfinance pioneer) on inclusive livelihood development and access to financial services. CBM is also in dialogue with the Village Savings and Loans organisation (VSL), with a view to includi
[normal]ng persons with disabilities. VSL is a pioneer in village savings and loans, and has nearly 
[normal]nine
[normal] million members, mostly in Africa.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]In recent years there has been marked growth in the number of persons with disabilities becoming involved in open employment, cooperatives, micro-finance and savings &amp; loans schemes. Last year, CBM skills development and work creation programmes reach over
[normal] 100,000 people with disabilities. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Participatory planning is used to involve the individual with a disability and his or her family, together with the economic realities of the community in which the individual lives, taking into account what products an
[normal]d services are in high demand and short supply. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A twin-track approach of economic empowerment of persons with disabilities, together with sustained advocacy for inclusive livelihood development at local, national and international levels has been shown t
[normal]o be a successful model of engagement.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Case Study: Inclusive Development through Organic Farming [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]“Inclusive Development through Organic Farming” is a five
[normal]-
[normal]year project
[normal] and initiative of 
[normal]CBM
[normal] partner Naman
[normal] Seva Samiti
[normal], with the aim of providing livelihood
[normal] opportunities for a total of 1,500 farmers with disabilities and their families in Madhya Pradesh
[normal],
[normal] central India. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This is the first project in India which trains people with disabilities in organic farming in their local language. Participants in the pr
[normal]ogramme include people with physical, hearing and visual impairments as well as parents of children with disabilities. During the project, farmers will develop a cooperative movement where they are responsible for the entire production and marketing cycle.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Each year, 300-350 farmers receive training in soil testing, the production of organic manure, crop selection and processing of products through a mix of both theory lessons at the training centre and practical sessions in the fields. Farmers also take p
[normal]art in exposure visits to learn from the experiences of other farmers’ 
[normal]groups and organisations in different parts of the country. In addition to training, Naman provides transportation, promotion and marketing support and reaches out to larger markets and
[normal] suppliers of bigger supermarkets wherever feasible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Naman’s advocacy activities at government level in Madhya Pradesh have led to the state government providing technical support for the project and declaring Athner block as an ‘organic block’. 
[normal]Already,
[normal] other 
[normal]organis
[normal]ations
[normal] are approaching Naman to share its experiences and gain help in establishing 
[normal]pilot projects
[normal] 
[normal]in other parts of India.
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Farmer showing her organic vegetable production[bold] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Most importantly, the project is bringing significant change 
[normal]to the lives of persons with disabilities and their families. Pe
[normal]rsons
[normal] with disabilities are leading a process of economic empowerment and agricultural innovation, changing perceptions within the wider community, giving hope to thousands of persons with dis
[normal]abilities in rural India. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]CBM and Inclusive Education[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]There is a growing recognition that the inclusion of children with disability in mainstream schools builds self-confidence and self-respect through social inclusion, as well as increasing employment choices. Governments around the world are therefore start
[normal]ing to introduce inclusive education as a strategy in their mainstream education programmes. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CBM is working with our partners to forward the inclusive education agenda through targeted programme work and advocacy initiatives in a number of inclusive educ
[normal]ation projects.
[normal] C
[normal]hallenges
[normal] of 
[normal]the q
[normal]uality of 
[normal]education
[normal] for all childre
[normal]n
[normal] (in particular
[normal] children wi
[normal]th 
[normal]disabilities
[normal])
[normal], 
[normal]ac
[normal]cessibility of school sanitation and toilets
[normal] 
[normal]also 
[normal]remain high on the 
[normal]CBM
[normal] agenda.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CBM is
[normal] also
[normal] a key partner in the Global Campaign for Ed
[normal]ucation 2014 which is highlighting the inclusion of 
[normal]c
[normal]hildren 
[normal]w
[normal]ith 
[normal]d
[normal]isability in Education.
