[normal]CBM and Disaster Preparedness[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]CBM knows that the involvement of pe
[normal]rsons
[normal] with disabilit
[normal]ies
[normal] disaster management planning saves lives.  
[normal]Disasters have a huge impact on human infrastructure, and livelihoods. The key 
[normal]to
[normal] diminishing their impact is to reduce people’s vulnerability. Through inclusive Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR) programmes, incorporated in human development plans and poverty 
[normal]reduction programmes, risks can be reduced and communities’ resilience to disasters can be strengthened.
[normal]Persons with disabilities are often overlooked throughout the disaster management cycle and especially during relief operations, and are seldom 
[normal]considered as important actors in conflict prevention even though they are often more exposed during conflicts and displacement
[normal]. The UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (CRPD), in its articles 11 and 32
[normal], requires that persons with di
[normal]sabilities benefit from and participate in disaster relief, emergency response and disaster risk reduction strategies 
[normal]as pe
[normal]rsons
[normal] with disabilit
[normal]ies
[normal] are the most vulnerable in a disaster situation. The disaster preparedness and disaster risk reduction traini
[normal]ng run by CBM partners in 
[normal]t
[normal]he Philippines before Typhoon Haiyan struck has shown how effective this can be through the number of lives saved.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CBM adheres to the 
[normal]k
[normal]ey principles for inclusive disaster risk reduction policies which include:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Case Study: Putting Disability on the agenda of Disaster Risk Mana[bold]gement[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The Disability 
[normal]I
[normal]nclusive Disaster Risk Reduction Network for Asia and Pacific participated in the Global Platform for Disaster Risk Management in Geneva in May 2013. The network achieved its objective of assuring that disability is included and 
[normal]mainstreamed across disaster risk reduction management projects 
[normal]and working towards a disability
[normal]-
[normal]inclusive post Hyogo Framework for Action. For the first time disability was included in the outcome document. 
[normal]“Even the best early warning systems and prepar
[normal]edness efforts to evacuate populations in dangers do not address fully the diversity of disabilities that we have in our societies. The only way to address this is to ensure that persons with disability are involved in the deism and planning of the systems
[normal] that are designed to protect the safety of the population in all countries.” 
[normal]Margareta Wahlstrom, Special Rep
[normal]resentative
[normal] for UNISDR.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CBM and Community Based Rehabilitation [bold]&#xa0;[bold]CBM has been instrumental is the adoption of the Community
[normal]-b
[normal]ased 
[normal]r
[normal]ehabilitation (CBR) approach which is now an integral part of most CBM supported partners approach to 
[normal]disability
[normal]-
[normal] inclu
[normal]sive development, ensuring that
[normal] projects and programmes meet the 
[normal]requirements
[normal] 
[normal]of people with disabilities and their families in their own
[normal] communities through a holistic approach to a person and their environment in the areas of health, education, livelihood, social inclusion, skill development and empowerment.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Case Study[bold]: Elim Programme, [bold]Igede Nigeria [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Christian Vocational Training C
[normal]entre “Elim” runs a 
[normal]c
[normal]ommunity
[normal]-
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]ased 
[normal]r
[normal]ehabilitation 
[normal]p
[normal]rogramme, 
[normal]aiming to empower and build the capacities of 
[normal]persons with disabilities
[normal]. It
[normal] covers a large rural area in Benue State in central Nigeria with a population of about 300,000. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Needs assessments 
[normal]by community workers 
[normal]clearly identify the problems faced by 
[normal]persons with disabilities
[normal] 
[normal]and mothers/parents who have children with disabilities in this region
[normal]. These include
[normal]: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Services 
[normal]are then 
[normal]offered to 
[normal]persons with disabilities
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]include eye surgery, orthopaedic surgery, 
[normal]rehabilitation services
[normal], special education for both 
[normal]people 
[normal]with 
[normal]hearing and visua
[normal]l impair
[normal]ments
[normal] and an economic integration programme. An orthopaedic workshop has also recently been developed. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Experts in education and physiotherapy provide additional support in the community
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The Elim
[normal] programme team also dedicates a significant amount of time and effort to raising awareness of disability within the local communities to reduce the stigma and discrimination that many 
